  "prompt_text": "Calculate the eigenvalues of the matrix [[2, 1], [1, 2]]. What do they tell us about the transformation?",
  "response_text": "To calculate the eigenvalues of the given matrix \\(\\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 2 \\end{bmatrix}\\), we need to find its characteristic polynomial and solve for the roots of that polynomial.\n\nThe characteristic polynomial \\(p(\\lambda)\\) is given by:\n\\[ p(\\lambda) = \\det(A - \\lambda I) \\]\n\nWhere \\(A\\) is the matrix, \\(\\lambda\\) is an eigenvalue, and \\(I\\) is the identity matrix.\n\nFor our matrix:\n\\[ A = \\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\\\ 1 & 2 \\end{bmatrix} \\]\n\nSo,\n\\[ A - \\lambda I = \\begin{bmatrix} 2 - \\lambda & 1 \\\\ 1 & 2 - \\lambda \\end{bmatrix} \\]\n\nNow, we compute the determinant:\n\\[ p(\\lambda) = \\det\\left( \\begin{bmatrix} 2 - \\lambda & 1 \\\\ 1 & 2 - \\lambda \\end{bmatrix} \\right) \\]\n\n\\[ p(\\lambda) = (2 - \\lambda)(2 - \\lambda) - (1)(1) \\]\n\n\\[ p(\\lambda) = (2 - \\lambda)^2 - 1 \\]\n\n\\[ p(\\lambda) = 4 - 4\\lambda + \\lambda^2 - 1 \\]\n\n\\[ p(\\lambda) = \\lambda^2 - 4\\lambda + 3 \\]\n\nNext, we set the characteristic polynomial equal to zero to find the eigenvalues:\n\\[ \\lambda^2 - 4\\lambda + 3 = 0 \\]\n\nThis is a quadratic equation, which can be factored as:\n\\[ (\\lambda - 1)(\\lambda - 3) = 0 \\]\n\nThus, the eigenvalues are:\n\\[ \\lambda_1 = 1 \\]\n\\[ \\lambda_2 = 3 \\]\n\n### Analysis of Eigenvalues\n\n1. **Eigenvalue \\(\\lambda_1 = 1\\)**:\n   - This value indicates that there is only one linearly independent eigenvector associated with it.\n   - In other words, the transformation corresponding to \\(\\lambda_1 = 1\\) does not change the direction of any vector; it only scales them proportionally.\n\n2. **Eigenvalue \\(\\lambda_2 = 3\\)**:\n   - This value also indicates that there is only one linearly independent eigenvector associated with it.\n   - Similar to \\(\\lambda_1\\), the transformation corresponding to \\(\\lambda_2 = 3\\) does not change the direction of any vector; it only scales them proportionally.\n\n### Implications\n\n- The eigenvalues \\(\\lambda_1 = 1\\) and \\(\\lambda_2 = 3\\) suggest that the transformation preserves the length of vectors but changes their",
